  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Sustainable Livelihoods For Beekeepers in Uganda</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Demand for locally-produced honey in Uganda is growing, with honey considered an important product to raise the incomes of rural families. It requires little capital and can be undertaken in remote areas, often by illiterate subsistence farmers. However, buying and selling arrangements between beekeepers, packers and the market are unreliable and offer little incentive for beekeepers to organise or increase production. The project will support beekeepers across Uganda by building the capacity of three institutions working nationally, regionally and locally. At a national level, TUNADO, will galvanise the sector and advocate for more support for beekeeping enterprises. At a regional level, Apitrade Africa will increase the visibility and improve the marketing techniques of beekeepers. At a local level KABECOS, a small beekeepers&#x2019; association in Kamwenge District, will become an effective marketing body for its 1,200 members. The project will improve the livelihoods of beekeepers and their families and increase total volumes of honey produced and sold by 53%. The project is follow on funding from a previous research grant which provided strong evidence of the need for this work and established productive working relationships between the four project partners. It is hoped that, with an additional &#xA3;2k investment, the project will support two of the Trade programme&#x2019;s learning questions</narrative>
  </description>
